						<div class=3D"two-col row">
							<div class=3D"main-content col-xl-9 col-lg-8">
								<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">When dealing with <a href=3D"h=
ttps://www.groundlabs.com/blog/is-cardholder-data-discovery-a-requirement-i=
n-pci-dss-4-0/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">cardholder data discover=
y projects</a>, we often get a lot of questions about credit card data form=
ats =E2=80=94 things like the PAN number, BIN ranges and Luhn checks</span>=
<span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">. </span><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;=
">We thought some clarification was needed so we will describe below what a=
 </span><i><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">PAN number</span></i><span sty=
le=3D"font-weight: 400;"> is made of, what </span><i><span style=3D"font-we=
ight: 400;">BIN ranges</span></i><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;"> refer t=
o, and how you can use </span><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">the <em>Luh=
n algorithm </em></span><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">(also know</span>=
<span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">n</span><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;"=
> as</span><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;"> Mod 10, and named after IBM s=
cientist Hans Peter Luhn</span><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">) to valid=
ate a credit card using pen and paper.</span></p>=20
<!--more--><h2>Three credit card data format components to know</h2>=20
<p>A credit card number, for example 1234 5678 1234 5678, consists of three=
 parts:</p>=20
<ol>=20
 <li><strong>The bank identification number <b>(BIN)</b>: </strong>The firs=
t six digits are the bank identification number (BIN) or issuer identificat=
ion number (IIN). <span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">This string of numbers =
</span>identifies the issuer of the card.</li>=20
 <li><strong>Account identification : </strong>The numbers between the bank=
 identification number and the check digit =E2=80=93which can be six to nin=
e digits long =E2=80=93 are used to identify the individual account associa=
ted with the payment card.</li>=20
 <li><strong>The check digit: </strong>The last digit is the check digit an=
d is added to validate the authenticity of the credit card number (based on=
 the Luhn algorithm).</li>=20
</ol>=20
<h2>Bank Identification Number (BIN) and Issuer Information Number (IIN) Ra=
nges<br> <a href=3D"https://www.groundlabs.com/compliance/pci-dss/"><br> </=
a><a href=3D"https://www.groundlabs.com/compliance/pci-dss/"><img loading=
=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter wp-image-5335 size-large"=
 src=3D"https://www.groundlabs.com/hs-fs/hubfs/Imported_Blog_Media/GL_blog-=
banners-2021_pcidss-1024x384-2.jpg?width=3D1024&amp;height=3D384&amp;name=
=3DGL_blog-banners-2021_pcidss-1024x384-2.jpg" alt=3D"Learn more about PCI =
DSS Compliance =E2=80=94 Ground Labs" width=3D"1024" height=3D"384"></a></h=
2>=20
<p>The first digit of the card represents the category of industry (IIN) th=
at issued your credit card. For example if you use VISA or MasterCard, your=
 card=E2=80=99s first digit should be either 4 or 5 as they are from the ba=
nking and <a href=3D"https://www.groundlabs.com/industry/financial-services=
/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener"><span style=3D"text-decoration: under=
line;">financial industry</span></a>. American Express is in the travel cat=
egory and cards issued by them have 3 as the first digit. <span style=3D"fo=
nt-weight: 400;">This is why some websites can automatically identify a val=
id card number after just one keystroke. </span></p>=20
<p>Below are some BIN numbers associated with related brands. As you can se=
e the length of a credit card will vary depending on the brand, and they ar=
e not all 16 digits.</p>=20
