<h2>Using the Luhn Algorithm to Verify a Payment Card</h2>=20
<p>The final digits of a credit card number is a check digit, akin to a che=
cksum.</p>=20
<p>The Luhn <span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">algorithm</span><span style=
=3D"font-weight: 400;">, </span><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">also know=
n </span>as a Mod 10 calculation, can be used to validate primary account n=
umbers.</p>=20
<h3><strong>How to perform a Luhn check&nbsp;</strong></h3>=20
<p>You can verify a credit card using the <span style=3D"font-weight: 400;"=
>Luhn algorithm</span> in a few simple steps:</p>=20
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 1. Write down the credi=
t card number:</p>=20
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">4417 1234 5678 9113</p>=20
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 2. Starting from the fi=
rst number, double every other digit.</p>=20
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">4(x2) 4 1(x2) 7 1(x2) 2 3(x2) 4 5(x2) 6 7(x2=
) 8 9(x2) 1 1(x2) 3</p>=20
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">The doubled numbers result in: 8 2 2 6 10 14=
 18 2</p>=20
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 3. If the result=
 of the doubling ends up with a two digits, then add those two digits toget=
her:</p>=20
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">10 =3D 1+0 14=3D 1+4 18=3D 1+8</p>=20
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 4. Add up all nu=
mbers: 8+4+2+7 + 2+2+6+4 + 1+0+6+1+4+8 + 1+8+1+2+3 =3D <strong>70</strong><=
/p>=20
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">If the final sum is divisible by 10, then th=
e credit card is valid. If it is not divisible by 10, the number is invalid=
 or fake.</p>=20
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">In the above example, credit card number 441=
7 1234 5678 9113 has passed the Luhn test.</p>=20
<h2>Credit card discovery made easy with Card Recon</h2>=20
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">The Luhn algorithm will detect almost =
any single-digit error, such as someone mistyping numbers when they put in =
their credit card</span><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">. T</span><span s=
tyle=3D"font-weight: 400;">he Luhn algorithm does not protect against malic=
ious attacks, nor is it intended to. It is primarily a safeguard against si=
mple user errors. Most credit cards and many government identification numb=
ers use this check as a simple method to distinguish valid numbers from ran=
dom digits.&nbsp;</span></p>=20
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">That said, your business doesn=E2=80=
=99t have to work out the Luhn algorithm by hand. A cardholder data discove=
ry tool, like </span><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Card Recon</span><sp=
an style=3D"font-weight: 400;">, can scan your systems to identify thousand=
s of credit, debit and pre-paid cards, and instantly determine which are va=
lid. This is a crucial step for complying with security standards like <a h=
ref=3D"https://www.groundlabs.com/blog/pci-dss-v4-0-1/" target=3D"_blank" r=
el=3D"noopener">PCI DSS</a> and privacy laws such as GDPR and more.&nbsp;</=
span></p>=20
<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><em><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Lear=
n more about how Ground Labs=E2=80=99 <a href=3D"https://www.groundlabs.com=
/card-recon/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">Card Recon</a> can help yo=
u identify and secure credit cards for PCI DSS compliance and more.</span><=
/em></p>
